Data Details

library(tidyverse)
library(jsonlite)

The two questions that I have been asked to answer to the Room Key Data Science Challenge are:

  • What factors correlate with users booking?
  • What can Room Key do to increase booking conversion rate?

To begin, I want to do an exploration of the details of the data set. This information will be the starting point for some exploratory data analysis.

Data Import

The first step is to import the data to R. The data is stored as a tab-separated value format with three columns. The elements of each column contain an entry for referrals, leads, and booking in JSON format.

room_key_data <- read_tsv("data.tsv", progress = FALSE)

With the data imported, I want to take a peak at what it looks like.

room_key_data

In this form the data is pretty difficult to parse. I want to take each column of the room_key_data object (referral, lead, and booking) and split them into individual data sets. These individual data sets can then be parsed by their JSON format and turned into a data frame.

Data Cleaning

The first step of the data cleaning will be to split each data set apart. For each of the data sets, I will filter out the null entries as these are ones that did not lead to any leads or booking. The filtering step will also occur for the referral set, but it should not lead to the removal of any entries. The fromJSON function will then be applied to every element of the column and a new data frame will be formed with all of the information spread out for each data set.

Referral

The first set to look at is the referral set.

referral <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(referral != "null") %>%
  .$referral %>% 
  map_df(fromJSON)

Note that converting this into a data frame is time intensive. Here is a peak at the completed data frame.

referral

Lead

Next I want to convert the lead column into a data frame.

lead <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(lead != "null") %>%
  .$lead %>% 
  map_df(fromJSON)

Here is the lead data set.

lead

Booking

Lastly, I want to convert the booking data set into a data frame.

booking <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(booking != "null") %>%
  .$booking %>% 
  map_df(fromJSON)

And here is the booking data set.

booking

Data Details

Now I want to explore the details of each data set. What kind of variables am I working with in each one?

Referral

In the referral data set there are 9 columns.

  • visitor-id
  • event-id
  • ts
  • type
  • location-tid
  • partner-code
  • check-in
  • check-out
  • udicode
room_key_data %>% 
  filter(booking != "null") %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>% 
  filter(rowname == 1) %>% 
  select(-rowname)

Doing a visual inspection of an observation that contains a referral, lead, and booking, it appears that the visitor-id variable is a unique identifier for a user/visitor. The event-id variable however is not a unique identifier of an observation within, but rather an identifier for an individual referral, lead, or booking event. That is to say, for a single row there are different event-id’s for each referral, lead, and booking event.

To get a sense of what each column contains I am going to do a few simple explorations. First, the total number of observations.

referral %>% 
  count()

event-id

Next, the number of distinct event-id’s.

referral %>% 
  distinct(`event-id`) %>% 
  count()

The number of distinct event-id’s and the total number of observations are equal, indicating that the event-id column does truly represent each unique referral event.

visitor-id

Next, I want to look at the visitor-id column.

referral %>% 
  distinct(`visitor-id`) %>% 
  count()

Here, the number of unique visitor id’s is less than the total number of observations. This indicates that there are a few return visitors to the site.

ts

Next, I want to understand what the ts column is. It appears to be a large number and may be a timestamp written in Unix time.

referral %>% 
  select(ts) %>% 
  mutate(timestamp = lubridate::as_datetime(ts))

The timestamps produced assuming that ts is in Unix time of seconds produces timestamps in the year 49757 which is obviously incorrect. If I assume that the ts column is actually in units of milliseconds then I get the following timestamps.

referral %>% 
  select(ts) %>% 
  mutate(timestamp = lubridate::as_datetime(ts / 1000)) %>% 
  summarize(min_date = min(timestamp), max_date = max(timestamp))

These timestamps match the date range given in the challenge prompt.

type

Next I want to determine how many type show up in the set.

referral %>% 
  distinct(type)

There is only one type that appears in this data set, so it is likely that the type can be discarded unless I plan to combine the three data sets together.

location-tid

Next is the location-tid column.

referral %>% 
  distinct(`location-tid`)

There are about 13k distinct elements in location-tid. How many times does each distinct element appear?

referral %>% 
  select(`location-tid`) %>% 
  group_by(`location-tid`) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

It looks like the largest appearance is made by NA. Additional, there appear to be many repeat appearances of these elements. This indicates that this may be a variable I can examine deeper. Assuming I can determine the origin of the NA elements.

Partner Code

Now, I want to look at the partner-code and see how many unique partners there are.

referral %>% 
  distinct(`partner-code`)

There are 7 unique partners that appear with the following frequency.

referral %>% 
  group_by(`partner-code`) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

check-in and check-out

Next, I want to examine the check-in and check-out columns. These are fairly self-explantory in that they are the dates the visitor wants to check in and check out for their trip. These variable may be of interest as either a way of looking at correlations between booking and check in date, correlations between book and length of trip, or correlations between booking and time between referral date and check-in date.

referral %>% 
  select(`check-in`, `check-out`) %>% 
  mutate(check_in = lubridate::ymd(`check-in`), 
         check_out = lubridate::ymd(`check-out`))

udicode

Next, I look at the udicode.

referral %>% 
  group_by(udicode) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

This is another variable that has a number of repeated values. This could be another variable to examine for correlations, though the vast majority of this variable is encoded as NA.

Lead

In the lead data set there are 5 columns:

  • visitor-id
  • event-id
  • ts
  • type
  • rate-partner

First, I want to verify that all of the columns similar to the same named columns in referral are truly similar.

lead %>% 
  count()
lead %>% 
  distinct(`event-id`) %>% 
  count()

As before, event-id is the number of unique lead events.

lead %>% 
  distinct(`visitor-id`) %>% 
  count()

Also as before, the visitor-id variable is unique for each visitor, but there are likely a few repeat visitors.

lead %>% 
  select(ts) %>% 
  mutate(timestamp = lubridate::as_datetime(ts / 1000)) %>% 
  summarize(min_date = min(timestamp), max_date = max(timestamp))

Here, ts appears to be the timestamp for when the lead event occured.

lead %>% 
  distinct(type)

As with the referral set, the type for lead only refers to the api used.

rate-partner

The only new variable in this set is rate-partner.

lead %>% 
  group_by(`rate-partner`) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

Like the partner-code variable from the referral data set, the rate-partner refers to the hotel group that the lead linked to.

Booking

In the booking data set there are 11 columns:

  • currency
  • nights
  • visitor-id
  • check-in
  • type
  • check-out
  • rate-partner
  • ts
  • rooms
  • event-id
  • total-amount

Some of these variables overlap with the variables from the previous sets. I first want to look at those variables and verify they respond similarly.

First, I want to verify that all of the columns similar to the same named columns in referral are truly similar.

booking %>% 
  count()
booking %>% 
  distinct(`event-id`) %>% 
  count()

As before, event-id is the number of unique booking events.

booking %>% 
  distinct(`visitor-id`) %>% 
  count()

Also as before, the visitor-id variable is unique for each visitor, but there are likely a few repeat visitors. For the booking data set, there are almost an equal number of visitors as unique events indicating that there are few repeat bookings from the same visitor in the time span recorded.

booking %>% 
  select(ts) %>% 
  mutate(timestamp = lubridate::as_datetime(ts / 1000)) %>% 
  summarize(min_date = min(timestamp), max_date = max(timestamp))

Here, ts appears to be the timestamp for when the booking event occured.

booking %>% 
  distinct(type)

As with the referral set, the type for booking only refers to the api used.

booking %>% 
  select(`check-in`, `check-out`) %>% 
  mutate(check_in = lubridate::ymd(`check-in`), 
         check_out = lubridate::ymd(`check-out`))
 4 failed to parse.

While looking at the check-in and check-out dates for the booking, there are four dates that apparently failed to parse. A further investigation of these dates showed that there are 10 check-out dates filled in with NA. Additionally, there are several dates, the four not parsed, that are in non-standard date formats.

booking %>% 
  filter(is.na(`check-out`)) %>% 
  mutate(check_in = lubridate::ymd(`check-in`), 
         check_out = lubridate::ymd(`check-out`))
 4 failed to parse.All formats failed to parse. No formats found.

The four check-in dates that can’t be parsed also have non-standard entries in some of the other elements. All of these come from the rate-partner CHC.

booking %>% 
  filter(`rate-partner` == "CHC")

Note that not all of the CHC bookings have the non-standard entry for nights or check-ins.

booking %>% 
  group_by(`rate-partner`) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

The rate-partner entries are similar to that in the lead data set.

currency

booking %>% 
  distinct(currency)

The currency column contains what type of currency was used to pay for the booking.

nights

booking %>% 
  distinct(nights)

The nights column is the number of nights a booking was made for. Note that there are some non-standard entries for the nights as discussed in the

rooms

booking %>% 
  group_by(rooms) %>% 
  count() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n))

Again, there are a few non-standard entries here including a few NA entries. These are likely from a hotel that did not report their rooms.

total-amount

booking %>% 
  select(currency, `total-amount`)

The total-amount column is simply the total amount of money paid for the booking. Note that there are a few NA entries.

Data Import and Cleaning Procedure

The following is a procedure to be used in the rest of the project for the import, organizing, and cleaning of the data. This will include creating a key for each data set for appropriate joining and the creation of a few new variables.

room_key_data <- read_tsv("data.tsv", progress = FALSE) %>% 
  rownames_to_column() %>% 
  rename(key = rowname) %>% 
  mutate(lead_event = !(lead == "null"), 
         booking_event = !(booking == "null"))
referral_key <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(referral != "null") %>% 
  select(key, lead_event, booking_event)
referral <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(referral != "null") %>%
  .$referral %>% 
  map_df(fromJSON) %>% 
  bind_cols(referral_key) %>% 
  select(key, everything())
lead_key <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(lead != "null") %>% 
  select(key)
lead <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(lead != "null") %>%
  .$lead %>% 
  map_df(fromJSON) %>% 
  bind_cols(lead_key) %>% 
  select(key, everything())
booking_key <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(booking != "null") %>% 
  select(key)
booking <- room_key_data %>% 
  filter(booking != "null") %>%
  .$booking %>%  
  map_df(fromJSON) %>% 
  bind_cols(booking_key) %>% 
  select(key, everything())
